&lt;p&gt;Ok, after much deliberation, I decided to go the "sort every column" route.
For future reference by anyone interested, here's the function I've added to my class - it's called once per every column I need ranked:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;   private function calculateRankings(&amp;amp;$employees, $columnName) {
        $comparer = "return (\$a[$columnName][0] == \$b[$columnName][0]) ? 0 :  (\$a[$columnName][0] &amp;gt; \$b[$columnName][0] ? -1 : 1);";
        usort($employees, create_function('$a,$b', $comparer));
        foreach($employees as $key =&amp;gt; &amp;amp;$employee) {
            $employee[$columnName][1] = $key + 1;
        }
    }
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The +1 is due to the keys being zero-based. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You prepare for this function by turning each field you need ranked into a 2-element array: the first ([0]) contains the value, and the second ([1]) will contain the rank in the end.&lt;br&gt;
I.e.: &lt;code&gt;$employees['salary'] = array(1550, 0);&lt;/code&gt;.
You then call the function like this:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;code&gt;$this-&amp;gt;calculateRankings($employees, 'salary');&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

